18.body:
This treats an umbrella request using different specific methods, depending on the method does. Keywords: series Spring Boot: FilterChain An HTTP request is passed through a series of filters ("filter chain") before rreaching the destination controller. This is an example of the Chain of Responsibility pattern beacuase it allows the filterrs to be organised in a chain. Each filter has the ability to either handle the request or pass it along. A common idiom is chain.doFilter Python content_filter = ContentFilter([offensive_filter, ads_filter, porno_video_filter])
filtered_content = content_filter.filter(content) class ContentFilter(object): def __init__(self, filters=None): self._filters = list() if filters is not None: self._filters += filters def filter(self, content): for filter in self._filters: content = filter(content) return content

You don’t have to keep inheriting. Instead of class DbObject: pass class User(DbObject): pass We can do class User: _methods = ['get', 'save', 'delete'] def __init__(self, methods): self._methods = methods def __getattr__(self, attr): if attr in self._methods: return getattr(self._methods, attr) def get(self): pass def save(self): pass def delete(self): pass Such that we have some users who can only get stuff user1 = User("get")
user1.get(...) And some users have only delete rights user2 = User("delete")

5.body: By depending on abstract types (like interfaces) instead of concrete types, you can reduce the coupling between different parts of a program, making it more flexible and easier to change and maintain.
5.title: Abstraction

6.body: aka "coding to interface" Code should depend on interface abstractions and not on concrete classes. This can increase the flexibility of the code. Different languages have different constructs for such abstractions: trait — Rust interface, abstract class — Java, Kotlin protocol — Swift abc.ABC — Python Some languages bank on the use of duck typing to achieve this abstraction — "if it looks like a duck, swims like a duck, and quacks like a duck, then it probably is a duck." Duck typing in Python Here is an example, though imo isn't idiomatic. def get_moving(bird): if hasattr(bird, "fly"): bird.fly() else: bird.run() Personally, me nolikey because of the use of the hasattr reflection here.
